Standard Oil of Ohio (Sohio) partnered with the innovative PV firm Energy Conversion Devices (ECD) to develop amorphous silicon technology (
 
  99
 ). In the mid-1980s, the parent company British Petroleum grew dissatisfied with the firm, whose unprofitable exploration and diversification strategies depressed the stock price. A new CEO was sent in to restructure the firm to maximize shareholder value (
 
  100
 ). Shortly thereafter, the firm sold off its stake in ECD, which instead partnered with Japanese firm Canon (
 
